    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-10-02T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-10-02T10:00:00-05:00" n="150"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d150">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.348 Z 4/169: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Robbins</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-10-02T16:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 2, 1924—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 2—2:54 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>200. Embassy’s 188, September 10, 3 p.m.<note n="5" xml:id="d150fn5">Not
                        printed.</note> Foreign Office now states informally that presumably
                    Zeppelin will fly to the United States under German flag and that consequently
                    German authorities should procure necessary permissions for flight over foreign
                    territories. In reply to verbal inquiry the Embassy has informally expressed
                    concurrence in the foregoing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robbins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
